          This routine should be of help not only to those AT&T people
          working in the New York area, since they are most likely to
          need such information, but also to AT&T people from other
          areas when they make trips to New York, since their
          knowledge of Manhattan avenues is probably limited.

     BBBBUUUUGGGGSSSS
          The results returned by this command are (hopefully)
          approximate to within one or two blocks.  In addition, most
          of the avenues known to this routine have numeric cross
          streets.  Avenues at the southern end of Manhattan, however,
          have _n_a_m_e_d cross streets and only limited information about
          them is available.

          Another "bug" has to do with the way Manhattan has named its
          avenues.  Several avenues are known by two names.  For
          example the avenue known to most New Yorkers as 6th Avenue
          is listed on maps and company letterheads as Avenue of the
          Americas.  Tenth Avenue becomes Amsterdam Avenue and Eighth
          Avenue becomes Central Park West when they get near Central
          Park.  Similarly, 6th, 7th, and 8th Avenues are renamed to
          Lenox Avenue, Adam Clayton Powell Boulevard, and Fredrick
          Douglas Boulevard, respectively, when they enter Harlem.
          Except for a stretch of about 8 blocks, 4th Avenue has been
          completely renamed Park Avenue.

